| 5,443,846\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 22.6\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2nd\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{Composition bar|85|350|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]5\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{Composition bar|43|208|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]4\n| style=\"background:#fcc; text-align:center;\"| No {{small|(2016\u201318)}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"| Yes {{small|(2018\u201319)}}\n|-\n! [[April 2019 Spanish general election|Apr-2019]]\n| 7,513,142\n| 28.7\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|123|350|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Green Arrow Up Darker.svg|10px]]38\n| {{Composition bar|123|208|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Green Arrow Up Darker.svg|10px]]81\n| style=\"background:#ffc; text-align:center;\"| New election\n|-\n! [[November 2019 Spanish general election|Nov-2019]]\n| 6,792,199\n| 28.0\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|120|350|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]3\n| {{Composition bar|93|208|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]30\n| style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"| Coalition\n|}\n\n===European Parliament===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:97%; text-align:left;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\"| [[European Parliament]]\n|-\n! width=\"75\"| Election\n! width=\"70\"| Votes\n! width=\"35\"| %\n! width=\"25\"| #\n! Seats\n! width=\"35\"| +/\u2013\n! Leading candidate\n|-\n! [[1987 European Parliament election in Spain|1987]]\n| 7,522,706\n| 39.1\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|28|60|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Fernando Mor\u00e1n (politician)|Fernando Mor\u00e1n]]\n|-\n! [[1989 European Parliament election in Spain|1989]]\n| 6,275,552\n| 39.6\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|27|60|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]1\n|-\n! [[1994 European Parliament election in Spain|1994]]\n| 5,719,707\n| 30.8\n| 2nd\n| {{Composition bar|22|64|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]5\n|-\n! [[1999 European Parliament election in Spain|1999]]\n| 7,477,823\n| 35.3\n| 2nd\n| {{Composition bar|24|64|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Green Arrow Up Darker.svg|10px]]2\n| [[Rosa D\u00edez]]\n|-\n! [[2004 European Parliament election in Spain|2004]]\n| 6,741,112\n| 43.5\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|25|54|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Green Arrow Up Darker.svg|10px]]1\n| [[Josep Borrell]]\n|-\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Spain|2009]]\n| 6,141,784\n| 38.8\n| 2nd\n| {{Composition bar|23|54|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]8\n| [[Juan Fernando L\u00f3pez Aguilar]]\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Spain|2014]]\n| 3,614,232\n| 23.0\n| 2nd\n| {{Composition bar|14|54|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Red Arrow Down.svg|10px]]9\n| [[Elena Valenciano]]\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Spain|2019]]\n| 7,369,789\n| 32.9\n| '''1st'''\n| {{Composition bar|20|54|hex={{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party/meta/color}}}}\n| [[File:Green Arrow Up Darker.svg|10px]]6\n| [[Josep Borrell]]\n|}\n\n==Terms==\n* [[Baron]]: unofficial term for the party's regional leaders. They can be very powerful, especially if they run an autonomous community. There have been conflicts between barons and the central directorate in the past. Some barons were [[Pasqual Maragall]] ([[Catalonia]]), who didn't run for re-election in 2006; [[Juan Carlos Rodr\u00edguez Ibarra]] ([[Extremadura]]), who did not run for re-election in 2007; [[Manuel Chaves (politician)|Manuel Chaves]] ([[Andalucia]]), who renounced Andalucia's presidency in 2009 to assume Third Vice Presidency of the Spanish Government; [[Jos\u00e9 Montilla]] ([[Catalonia]]), now opposition leader. The term bar\u00f3n is more colloquial than official, representing the great power regional leaders have in the party, but it has been falling out of use since 2008.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n* ''Compa\u00f1ero'' (\"companion\", \"comrade\"): a term of address among Socialists, analogous to the English [[comrade]] and the Russian [[tovarisch]].\n* Currents: there have been several internal groups within PSOE, based on personal or ideological affinities. Some of them have ended with separation from PSOE. The failed trial of [[primary election]]s for PSOE candidates was an attempt to conciliate currents. Examples of currents are \"Guerristas\" (followers of [[Alfonso Guerra]]), \"[[Renovadores]]\" (renewers, right-wing of the party) or Izquierda Socialista (Socialist Left).\n\n== Historical leaders ==\n{| width=100%\n|- valign =\"top\"\n|width=30%|\n{| class=wikitable\n! President\n! Term\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Pablo Iglesias Posse|Pablo Iglesias]] \n| 1879\u20131925\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Juli\u00e1n Besteiro]]\n| 1925\u20131931\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Remigio Cabello]]\n| 1931\u20131932\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Francisco Largo Caballero]]\n| 1932\u20131935\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Indalecio Prieto]]\n| 1935\u20131948\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Trif\u00f3n G\u00f3mez]]\n| 1948\u20131955\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| Vacant\n| 1955\u20131964\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Pascual Tom\u00e1s]]\n| 1964\u20131967\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Ram\u00f3n Rubial]]\n| 1967\u20131970\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| In exile\n| 1970\u20131976\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Ram\u00f3n Rubial]]\n| 1976\u20131999\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Manuel Chaves (politician)|Manuel Chaves]]\n| 1999\u20132012\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Gri\u00f1\u00e1n]]\n| 2012\u20132014\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Micaela Navarro]]\n| 2014\u20132016\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Cristina Narbona]]\n| 2017\u2013\n|}\n|width=30%|\n{| class=wikitable\n! Secretary-General\n! Term\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Ram\u00f3n Lamoneda]] \n| 1936\u20131944\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Rodolfo Llopis]]\n| 1944\u20131972\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| ''In exile''\n| 1972\u20131974\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n| 1974\u20131997\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Joaqu\u00edn Almunia]]\n| 1997\u20132000\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]]\n| 2000\u20132012\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]\n| 2012\u20132014\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez]]\n| 2014\u20132016; 2017\u2013\n|}\n|width=30%|\n{| class=wikitable\n! Prime Ministers of Spain\n! Term\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Francisco Largo Caballero]] \n| 1936\u20131937\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Juan Negr\u00edn L\u00f3pez]]\n| 1937\u20131939\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]]\n| 1982\u20131996\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]]\n| 2004\u20132011\n\n|-----style=\"background-color:#FFFFFF\"\n| [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez]]\n| 2018\u2013\n|}\n|}\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETIAL ORDER -->\n\n==Notable members==\n{{For|a list of all PSOE members with an English Wikipedia article|Category:Spanish Socialist Workers' Party politicians}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Politics of Spain]]\n*[[List of 