\u00e1nea|publisher=[[University of Salamanca]]|location=Salamanca|year=1983|volume=1|first=Santos|last=Juli\u00e1|title=Corporativistas obreros y reformadores pol\u00edticos: crisis y escisi\u00f3n del PSOE en la II Rep\u00fablica|issn=0213-2087|ref=harv|pages=41\u201352}}\n* {{cite journal|title=La cuesti\u00f3n territorial en el PSOE durante la II Rep\u00fablica|first=Daniel|last=Molina Jim\u00e9nez|location=Le\u00f3n|journal=Estudios Human\u00edsticos. Historia|issn=1696-0300|issue=12|year=2013|publisher=[[University of Le\u00f3n]]|url=http://revpubli.unileon.es/index.php/EEHHHistoria/article/view/968/842|pages=259\u2013287|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Coming of the Spanish Civil War|first=Paul|last=Preston|author-link=Paul Preston |year=1978|isbn=978-0-333-23724-3}}\n* {{cite journal|issn=1575-0361|url=https://recyt.fecyt.es/index.php/Hyp/article/view/44520/26097|first=Alejandro|last=Quiroga Fern\u00e1ndez de Soto|issue=20|year=2008|title=Amistades peligrosas. La izquierda y los nacionalismos catalanes y vascos (1975-2008)|journal=Historia y Pol\u00edtica. Ideas, procesos y movimientos sociales|location=Madrid|ref=harv|publisher=[[Complutense University of Madrid|UCM]]; [[Centro de Estudios Pol\u00edticos y Constitucionales|CEPC]] & [[Universidad Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n a Distancia|UNED]]|pages=97\u2013127}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Robles Egea|first=Antonio|title=Las coaliciones de izquierdas en Francia y Espa\u00f1a (1899-1939)|year=2015|url=https://journals.openedition.org/ccec/5404|issn=1957-7761|journal=Cahiers de civilisation espagnole contemporaine|issue=2|publisher=[[Paris Nanterre University]]|location=Paris|doi=10.4000/ccec.5404}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Agony of Spanish Liberalism. From Revolution to Dictatorship 1913\u201323|editor=Francisco J. Romero Salvad\u00f3 |editor2=Angel Smith|publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|year=2010|isbn=978-1-349-36383-4|pages=62\u201391|chapter=Spain's Revolutionary Crisis of 1917: A Reckless Gamble|first=Francisco J.|last=Romero Salvad\u00f3|doi=10.1057/9780230274648|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation|title=Votos ponderados: sistemas electorales y sobrerrepresentaci\u00f3n distrital|first=Diego|last=Reynoso|publisher=FLACSO M\u00e9xico|year=2004|isbn=978-970-701-521-0|at=249|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0TyVQllO9pAC}}\n* {{cite journal|author-link=Manuel Tu\u00f1\u00f3n de Lara|first=Manuel|ref=harv|last=Tu\u00f1\u00f3n de Lara|title=Transformaciones Pol\u00edticas e Ideol\u00f3gicas de Espa\u00f1a durante el Primer Tercio del Siglo XX (1898-1936)|pages=231\u2013259|journal=Historia Contempor\u00e1nea|publisher=[[University of the Basque Country]]|location=Bilbao|issue=4|issn=1130-2402|url=http://www.ehu.eus/ojs/index.php/HC/article/viewFile/19288/17393}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Desarrollo y debates en los grupos anarquistas de la FAI en el Madrid republicano|first=Juli\u00e1n|last=Vadillo|pages=27\u201365|journal=Germinal: Revista de estudios libertarios|issn=1886-3019|issue=4|year=2007|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Partido Socialista Obrero Espa\u00f1ol}}\n* [http://www.psoe.es/ Official site]\n\n{{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party}}\n{{Spain political parties}}\n{{Party of European Socialists}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Spanish Socialist Workers' Party| ]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1879]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in Spain]]\n[[Category:Full member parties of the Socialist International]]\n[[Category:Party of European Socialists member parties]]\n[[Category:Members of the Labour and Socialist International]]\n[[Category:Second International]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Progressive Alliance]]\n", "name_user": "Jglezstu7", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_Socialist_Workers%27_Party"}
{"title_page": "Nejib Belkadhi", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian actor, film director and film producer}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata |fetchwikidata=ALL\n|name              = Nejib Belkadhi\n|native_name       = \u0646\u062c\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0636\u064a\n|native_name_lang  = Arabic\n|caption           = Nejib Belkadhi, February 2015.\n|birth_place       = [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]\n|nationality       = [[Tunisian people|Tunisian]]\n|occupation        = [[Actor]], [[Film director|Director]]\n}}\n'''Nejib Belkadhi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u062c\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0636\u064a}}; born May 13, 1972 in [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]) is a Tunisian actor and director.<ref name=\"tunisia-live\">{{cite web |title=Nejib Belkadhi |url=http://www.tunisia-live.net/2011/08/28/nejib-belkadhi/ |website=tunisia-live.net |accessdate=11 April 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref name=\"lepoint\">{{cite news|url= http://afrique.lepoint.fr/culture/nejib-belkadhi-regarde-moi-est-avant-tout-une-ode-a-la-difference-06-12-2018-2277218_2256.php|title= Cin\u00e9ma - Nejib Belkadhi : \u00ab \"Regarde-moi\" est avant tout une ode \u00e0 la diff\u00e9rence \u00bb|date= December 6, 2018|work= LE Point Alfrique}}</ref>\n== Education ==\nHe studied marketing and management at the [[Carthage High Commercial Studies Institute]] in [[Carthage]], before he started a career in arts.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web |title=PARK CITY \u201907 INTERVIEW, Nejib Belkadhi |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2007/01/park-city-07-interview-nejib-belkadhi-our-approach-was-to-stick-to-his-amateur-logic-without-fa-75267/ |website=indiewire.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nNejib had his first acting role in ''Hbiba Msika'' (''Dancer of the Flame''), a film by [[Salma Baccar]], in 1995. He then starred in Mohamed Kouka\u2019s play ''Madrasat Nisaa''(\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0633\u0627\u0621 / ''The Women's School''), however, Nejib's best success was in the series ''Khotab Albeb'' (\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0637\u0627\u0628 \u0639\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0628 /''Many Fiancees''), appearing in both volumes 1 and 2 (1996-1998) for the director,\nSleh Essid.\n\nNejib Belkadhi began his career in directing during 1998 on the TV network ''Canal+ Horizons'', covering the [[Carthage Film Festival]], before creating the network's most successful TV show: ''Chams Alik'' (\u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0643 ), whose concept revolutionized the Tunisian TV scene. He conceived, produced and co-presented the show from 1999 to 2001.\n\nIn 2002, he founded Propaganda Productions, with his friend Imed Marzouk, and in 2003 he directed and produced a socio-critical fake reality show called ''Dima Lebess'' (\u062f\u064a\u0645\u0627 \u0644\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0633 /''Always fine''), which was broadcast on the ''Canal21'' TV channel.\n\nHe directed his first movie in 2005, a short film called ''Tsawer'' (\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0648\u0631/''Pic''), with a screenplay of Souad Ben Slimane.\n\n''[[VHS Kahloucha]]'' (2006), his first feature documentary film, was screened to great acclaim at international film festivals, including Cannes (2006), Philadelphia (2007), Sundance l (2007) and Dubai (2007), and it was his most successful work to date.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/>\n\nHis last movie, ''[[Bastardo (film)|Bastardo]]'', was screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] in September 2013.<ref name=\"lepoint\"/>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Actor ===\n==== Cinema ====\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* [[1994]] : ''[[La Danse du feu]]'' by [[Salma Baccar]]: As Mimouni\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Season of Men]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]\n* [[2000]] : ''[[Tomrorrow, I'll burn]]'' by [[Mohammed Ben Isma\u00efl]]\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]\n* [[2003]] : ''[[Bedwin Hacker]]'' by [[Nadia El Fani]]\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Ghasra]]'' (Short film) by [[Jamil Najjar]]\n* [[2017]] : ''[[When the sky starts To Scream]]'' by [[Kais M\u00e9jri]]\n* [[2017]] : ''[[Astra]]'' by [[Nidhal Guiga]]\n* [[2018]] : ''[[ Watch Me]]'' by [[Nejib Belkadhi]]\n}}\n\n==== Television ====\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[1996]]-[[1997]] : ''[[El Khottab Al Bab]]'' by [[Slaheddine Essid]]\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Le Treasure of Damascus]]'' by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda S\u00e1nchez]]\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Loutil]]'' (The Hostel) by [[Slaheddine Essid]]\n* [[2008]] : ''[[Weld Ettalyena]]'' by [[Nejib Belkadhi]]\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Lilet Chak]]'' (The Night of Doubt) by [[Majdi Smiri]]\n* [[2016]] : ''[[The President]]'' by [[Jamil Najjar]]\n* [[2018]] : ''[[Tej El Hadhra]]'' by [[Sami Fehri]] : As General Osman\n* [[2019]] : ''[[The Affaire 460]]'' by [[Majdi Smiri]]\n}}\n\n=== Director ===\n==== Cinema ====\n* [[2005]]: [[Tsawer]] (Short film)\n* [[2006]]: [[VHS Kahloucha]] (Documentary)\n* [[2013]]: [[Bastardo (film)|Bastardo]] (English) (Feature film)\n* [[2014]]: ''Seven & A Half]]'' (Documentary)\n* [[2018]]: ''[[Watch-Me]]'' (Feature film)\n\n==== Television ====\n* [[1999]]-[[2001]]: ''[[Chams Alik]]''\n* [[2002]]: ''[[Dima Labess]]''\n* [[2008]]: ''[[Weld Ettalyena]]'' ( The Son of The Italian)\n* [[2020]]: ''[[The Animator and the Tramp]]''\n\n== Honours ==\n* [[2007]]: [[Knight of the Tunisian Order of Merit]]<ref>{{cite journal |title=Decrees and orders |journal=[[Official Gazette of the Republic of Tunisia]] |date=26 June 2007 |issue=51 |page=2223 |url=http://www.cnudst.rnrt.tn/jortsrc/2007/2007f/jo0512007.pdf |accessdate=11 April 2020 |language=fr |issn=0330-7921}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:Nejib Belkadhi|Nejib Belkadhi}}\n*[http://www.sharjahart.org/people/people-by-alphabet/b/belkadhi-najib Biography from the Sharjah Art Foundation]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/199738/Nejib-Belkadhi Actor/Director's Profile on NYTimes.com]\n*[http://www.indiewire.com/article/park_city_07_interview_nejib_belkadhi_our_approach_was_to_stick_to_his_amat Interview with Nejib Belkadhi on Indiewire]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131009125706/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/festival/2013/bastardo Nejib Belkadhi's Movie ''Bastardo'' in TIFF-festival 2013]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Belkadhi, Nejib}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tunis]]\n[[Category:Tunisian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian actor, film director and film producer}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata |fetchwikidata=ALL\n|name              = Nejib Belkadhi\n|native_name       = \u0646\u062c\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0636\u064a\n|native_name_lang  = Arabic\n|caption           = Nejib Belkadhi, February 2015.\n|birth_place       = [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]\n|nationality       = [[Tunisian people|Tunisian]]\n|occupation        = [[Actor]], [[Film director|Director]]\n}}\n'''Nejib Belkadhi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u062c\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0636\u064a}}; born May 13, 1972 in [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]) is a Tunisian actor and director.<ref name=\"tunisia-live\">{{cite web |title=Nejib Belkadhi |url=http://www.tunisia-live.net/2011/08/28/nejib-belkadhi/ |website=tunisia-live.net |accessdate=11 April 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref name=\"lepoint\">{{cite news|url= http://afrique.lepoint.fr/culture/nejib-belkadhi-regarde-moi-est-avant-tout-une-ode-a-la-difference-06-12-2018-2277218_2256.php|title= Cin\u00e9ma - Nejib Belkadhi : \u00ab \"Regarde-moi\" est avant tout une ode \u00e0 la diff\u00e9rence \u00bb|date= December 6, 2018|work= LE Point Alfrique}}</ref>\n== Education ==\nHe studied marketing and management at the [[Carthage High Commercial Studies Institute]] in [[Carthage]], before he started a career in arts.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web |title=PARK CITY \u201907 INTERVIEW, Nejib Belkadhi |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2007/01/park-city-07-interview-nejib-belkadhi-our-approach-was-to-stick-to-his-amateur-logic-without-fa-75267/ |website=indiewire.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nNejib had his first acting role in ''Hbiba Msika'' (''Dancer of the Flame''), a film by [[Salma Baccar]], in 1995. He then starred in Mohamed Kouka\u2019s play ''Madrasat Nisaa''(\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0633\u0627\u0621 / ''The Women's School''), however, Nejib's best success was in the series ''Khotab Albeb'' (\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0637\u0627\u0628 \u0639\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0628 /''Many Fiancees''), appearing in both volumes 1 and 2 (1996-1998) for the director,\nSleh Essid.\n\nNejib Belkadhi began his career in directing during 1998 on the TV network ''Canal+ Horizons'', covering the [[Carthage Film Festival]], before creating the network's most successful TV show: ''Chams Alik'' (\u0634\u0645\u0633 \u0639\u0644\u064a\u0643 ), whose concept revolutionized the Tunisian TV scene. He conceived, produced and co-presented the show from 1999 to 2001.\n\nIn 2002, he founded Propaganda Productions, with his friend Imed Marzouk, and in 2003 he directed and produced a socio-critical fake reality show called ''Dima Lebess'' (\u062f\u064a\u0645\u0627 \u0644\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0633 /''Always fine''), which was broadcast on the ''Canal21'' TV channel.\n\nHe directed his first movie in 2005, a short film called ''Tsawer'' (\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0648\u0631/''Pic''), with a screenplay of Souad Ben Slimane.\n\n''[[VHS Kahloucha]]'' (2006), his first feature documentary film, was screened to great acclaim at international film festivals, including Cannes (2006), Philadelphia (2007), Sundance l (2007) and Dubai (2007), and it was his most successful work to date.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/>\n\nHis last movie, ''[[Bastardo (film)|Bastardo]]'', was screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] in September 2013.<ref name=\"lepoint\"/>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Actor ===\n==== Cinema ====\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* [[1994]] : ''[[La Danse du feu]]'' by [[Salma Baccar]]: As Mimouni\n* [[2000]] : ''[[The Season of Men]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]\n* [[2000]] : ''[[Tomrorrow, I'll burn]]'' by [[Mohammed Ben Isma\u00efl]]\n* [[2002]] : ''[[The magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]\n* [[2003]] : ''[[Bedwin Hacker]]'' by [[Nadia El Fani]]\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Ghasra]]'' (Short film) by [[Jamil Najjar]]\n* [[2017]] : ''[[When the sky starts To Scream]]'' by [[Kais M\u00e9jri]]\n* [[2017]] : ''[[Astra]]'' by [[Nidhal Guiga]]\n* [[2018]] : ''[[ Watch Me]]'' by [[Nejib Belkadhi]]\n}}\n\n==== Television ====\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[1996]]-[[1997]] : ''[[El Khottab Al Bab]]'' by [[Slaheddine Essid]]\n* [[1998]] : ''[[Le Treasure of Damascus]]'' by [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda S\u00e1nchez]]\n* [[2004]] : ''[[Loutil]]'' (The Hostel) by [[Slaheddine Essid]]\n* [[2008]] : ''[[Weld Ettalyena]]'' by [[Nejib Belkadhi]]\n* [[2015]] : ''[[Lilet Chak]]'' (The Night of Doubt) by [[Majdi Smiri]]\n* [[2016]] : ''[[The President]]'' by [[Jamil Najjar]]\n* [[2018]] : ''[[Tej El Hadhra]]'' by [[Sami Fehri]] : As General Osman\n* [[2019]] : ''[[The Affaire 460]]'' by [[Majdi Smiri]]\n}}\n\n=== Director ===\n==== Cinema ====\n* [[2005]]: [[Tsawer]] (Short film)\n* [[2006]]: [[VHS Kahloucha]] (Documentary)\n* [[2013]]: [[Bastardo (film)|Bastardo]] (English) (Feature film)\n* [[2014]]: ''Seven & A Half]]'' (Documentary)\n* [[2018]]: ''[[Watch-Me]]'' (Feature film)\n\n==== Television ====\n* [[1999]]-[[2001]]: ''[[Chams Alik]]''\n* [[2002]]: ''[[Dima Labess]]''\n* [[2008]]: ''[[Weld Ettalyena]]'' ( The Son of The Italian)\n* [[2020]]: ''[[The Animator and the Tramp]]''\n\n== Honours ==\n* 2007: Knight of the Tunisian Order of Merit<ref>{{cite journal |title=Decrees and orders |journal=[[Official Gazette of the Republic of Tunisia]] |date=26 June 2007 |issue=51 |page=2223 |url=http://www.cnudst.rnrt.tn/jortsrc/2007/2007f/jo0512007.pdf |accessdate=11 April 2020 |language=fr |issn=0330-7921}}</ref>\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:Nejib Belkadhi|Nejib Belkadhi}}\n*[http://www.sharjahart.org/people/people-by-alphabet/b/belkadhi-najib Biography from the Sharjah Art Foundation]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/199738/Nejib-Belkadhi Actor/Director's Profile on NYTimes.com]\n*[http://www.indiewire.com/article/park_city_07_interview_nejib_belkadhi_our_approach_was_to_stick_to_his_amat Interview with Nejib Belkadhi on Indiewire]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131009125706/http://tiff.net/filmsandschedules/festival/2013/bastardo Nejib Belkadhi's Movie ''Bastardo'' in TIFF-festival 2013]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Belkadhi, Nejib}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tunis]]\n[[Category:Tunisian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Nesrine1984", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nejib_Belkadhi"}
{"title_page": "Chennaiyin FC", "text_new": "{{short description|An Indian Super League football club based in Chennai, Tamil Nadu}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Chennaiyin F.C.\n| image = Official Chennaiyin FC Logo.png\n| image_size = 240px\n| fullname = Chennaiyin Football Club, \u0b9a\u0bc6\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b8e\u0b83\u0baa\u0bcd.\u0b9a\u0bbf \n| founded = {{start date and age|df=yes|2014|8|28}}\n| ground = [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium (Chennai)|Marina Arena]], [[Chennai]]\n| capacity = 40,000 (ISL) <ref name=\"SDAT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdat.tn.gov.in/index.php/infrastructure/stadia/jawaharlal-nehru-stadium-chennai|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318154030/http://www.sdat.tn.gov.in/index.php/infrastructure/stadia/jawaharlal-nehru-stadium-chennai|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 March 2014|title=Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Chennai|publisher=SDAT, Government of Tamil Nadu|access-date=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Abhishek Bachchan]] <br>[[MS Dhoni]] <br> Vita Dani \n| manager = [[Owen Coyle]]\n| league = {{Indian football  updater|Chennai}}  \n \n| season = [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season|2019-20]]\n \n| position = Regular season: 4th <br/> Playoffs: Runner-up\n| current = 2019\u201320 Chennaiyin FC season\n| website = http://chennaiyinfc.com/\n| pattern_la1  = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b1   = _vneckwhite\n| pattern_ra1  = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh1  = _whitebottom\n| pattern_so1  = _1415h\n| leftarm1     = 000080\n| body1        = 000080\n| rightarm1    = 000080\n| shorts1      = 000080\n| socks1       = 000080\n| pattern_la2  = _navyborder\n| pattern_b2   = _vnecknavy\n| pattern_ra2  = _navyborder\n| pattern_sh2  = _navybottom\n| pattern_so2  = _top_on_blue\n| leftarm2     = \n| body2        = \n| rightarm2    = \n| shorts2      = \n| socks2       = 000080\n| pattern_la3  = _navyborder\n| pattern_b3   = _vnecknavy\n| pattern_ra3  = _navyborder\n| pattern_sh3  = _navybattom\n| pattern_so3  = _1415h\n| leftarm3     = FFDF00\n| body3        = FFDF00\n| rightarm3    = FFDF00\n| shorts3      = FFDF00\n| socks3       = FFDF00\n\n}}\n\n'''Chennaiyin F.C.''' is a professional [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]. They compete in the [[Indian Super League]] under licence from the [[All India Football Federation]] (AIFF). The club was founded in August 2014 during the [[2014 Indian Super League season|inaugural season of the Indian Super League]]. Chennaiyin won the [[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season]], also having won it previously in [[2015 Indian Super League season|2015]] season, making them the  winners (2) \n\nThe franchise is owned by Vita Dani, [[Bollywood]] actor [[Abhishek Bachchan]] and [[India national cricket team|Indian cricketer]] [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141006/sports-football/article/dhoni-becomes-isl-team-chennaiyin-fc-co-owner|title=Dhoni becomes ISL team Chennaiyin FC co-owner|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|access-date=6 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007051743/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141006/sports-football/article/dhoni-becomes-isl-team-chennaiyin-fc-co-owner|archive-date=7 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The team's name ''Chennaiyin FC'' means ''Chennai's football club'' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] where the 'yin' suffix is similar to [[Apostrophe s|a possessive 's']] in English.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tntmagazine.in/isl-chennaiyin-fc-official-logo-unveiled/|title=Chennaiyin logo revealed|access-date=4 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141104165902/http://www.tntmagazine.in/isl-chennaiyin-fc-official-logo-unveiled/|archivedate=4 November 2014}}</ref> The team's logo is the ''Dhrishti Bommai'', a representation of chasing away negativity and preserving positivity in the [[Tamil culture]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sudarshan|first1=N.|title=Chennaiyin Football gets Italian seasoning|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chennaiyin-football-gets-italian-seasoning/article6436620.ece|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=5 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606043000/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/chennaiyin-football-gets-italian-seasoning/article6436620.ece|archive-date=6 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nWhen the [[Indian Super League]] was founded in 2014, the city of [[Chennai]] was one of the nine proposed cities up for franchise bidding.<ref>{{cite web|title=Business giants join forces to launch Indian Super League|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/4631/soccerex/2013/10/22/4350862/business-giants-join-forces-to-launch-indian-super-league|website=Goal.com|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018202518/http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/4631/soccerex/2013/10/22/4350862/business-giants-join-forces-to-launch-indian-super-league|archive-date=18 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> However, on 11 April 2014 it was reported that Chennai's main bidder, a consortium led by [[Sunil Gavaskar]] would drop out due to commitments with the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chennai unlikely to have an ISL team|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Chennai-unlikely-to-have-an-ISL-team/articleshow/33624463.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423132004/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Chennai-unlikely-to-have-an-ISL-team/articleshow/33624463.cms|archive-date=23 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Then, in August 2014, with two months before the [[2014 Indian Super League season|2014 ISL season]], the Bangalore owners [[Sun Group]] dropped out due to disputes with the organizers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mergulhao|first1=Marcus|title=Now, Sun Group opts out of Indian Super League|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Now-Sun-Group-opts-out-of-Indian-Super-League/articleshow/40163965.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817121223/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Now-Sun-Group-opts-out-of-Indian-Super-League/articleshow/40163965.cms|archive-date=17 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Initially reports came out that the ISL organizers were looking for bidders for new owners for the Bangalore franchise before it was revealed that [[Ronnie Screwvala]]  and actor [[Abhishek Bachchan]] would together bid for a Chennai team instead of a Bangalore franchise.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Suchindran|first1=Aravind|title=Screwvala, Abhishek may bid for Chennai franchise|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Screwvala-Abhishek-may-bid-for-Chennai-franchise/articleshow/40313996.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822205914/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Screwvala-Abhishek-may-bid-for-Chennai-franchise/articleshow/40313996.cms|archive-date=22 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Foundation===\nOn 14 August 2014, it was reported that ISL officials were inspecting the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium (Chennai)|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]] in Chennai for the proposed team.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mergulhao|first1=Marcus|title=ISL: Draft for overseas players on August 21|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/ISL-Draft-for-overseas-players-on-August-21/articleshow/40244205.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021105648/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/ISL-Draft-for-overseas-players-on-August-21/articleshow/40244205.cms|archive-date=21 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Finally, the team was bid for by actor [[Abhishek Bachchan]] and Vita Dani. On 12 September 2014, Italian World Cup winner [[Marco Materazzi]] was hired as player-manager.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suchindran|first1=Aravind|title=Marco Materazzi to manage Chennai Titans|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Marco-Materazzi-to-manage-Chennai-Titans/articleshow/42334829.cms|accessdate=12 September 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=12 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915133420/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Marco-Materazzi-to-manage-Chennai-Titans/articleshow/42334829.cms|archive-date=15 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Then, on 6 October 2014, the Former Indian cricket captain, [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]] became the joint co-owner of the club. The club officially launched their jersey on 9 October 2014 but had changed their home jersey's pattern in the [[2018\u201319 Indian Super League season]].\n\n===Marco Materazzi era (2014\u20132016)===\n[[File:Marco materazzi CFC 2014-2016.jpg|thumb|[[Marco Materazzi]] was the head coach of Chennaiyin FC from 2014 to 2016]]\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n| GK_nat  = ARM | GK  = [[Apoula Edel|Edel Bete]]\n| RB_nat = IND | RB = [[Mehrajuddin Wadoo|Wadoo]]\n| RCB_nat = FRA | RCB  =  [[Bernard Mendy|Mendy]]\n| LCB_nat = BRA | LCB =[[Ma\u00edlson Alves|Ma\u00edlson]]\n| LB_nat = IND | LB = [[Dhanachandra Singh|D Singh]]\n| RCM_nat = IND | RCM  =  [[Harmanjot Khabra|Khabra]]\n| LCM_nat  = IND| LCM  = [[Thoi Singh|Thoi]]\n| DM_nat  = ITA| DM =  [[Manuele Blasi|Blasi]]\n| RW_nat  =IND | RW  = [[Jeje Lalpekhlua|Jeje]]\n| LW_nat  =IND | LW  = [[Bruno Pelissari|Pelissari]]\n| CF_nat  = COL| CF  = [[Stiven Mendoza|Mendoza]]\n|caption=Lineup against [[FC Goa]] in [[2015 Indian Super League Final]]\n|\n}}\n\nOn 15 October 2014, Chennaiyin won their first Indian Super League fixture with a 2\u20131 victory at [[FC Goa]]. The goals were scored by [[Balwant Singh (footballer)|Balwant Singh]], who became the first Indian player to score in the competition, and the former Brazil international [[Elano]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Raj|first1=Rohan|title=ISL: Record-breaking Chennaiyin FC romp to 2\u20131 win over FC Goa|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-chennaiyin-fc-vs-fc-goa-live-indian-super-league-match-4-nehru-stadium/1/395917.html|accessdate=15 October 2014|work=[[India Today]]|date=15 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015231348/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-chennaiyin-fc-vs-fc-goa-live-indian-super-league-match-4-nehru-stadium/1/395917.html|archive-date=15 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 November 2014, the club brought [[Alessandro Nesta]], who won the World Cup for Italy out of retirement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Jack|title=Alessandro Nesta comes out of retirement to join Indian Super League side Chennaiyin|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2014/11/28/6601801/alessandro-nesta-comes-out-of-retirement-to-join-indian|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=Goal.com|date=28 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141130144711/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2014/11/28/6601801/alessandro-nesta-comes-out-of-retirement-to-join-indian|archive-date=30 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The team finished its 14-game regular season in first place in the league. In the semi finals, the team lost the first leg 3\u20130 to [[Kerala Blasters]]. In the second leg, they managed to overturn the deficit by leading 3\u20130 in regular time. However, a 117th-minute goal by [[Stephen Pearson]] sent Kerala through to the finals.\n\nFor the [[2015 Chennaiyin FC season|Second Season]] of [[Indian Super League]], they managed to retain six players namely, [[Balwant Singh (footballer)|Balwant Singh]], [[Jayesh Rane]], [[Dhanachandra Singh]], [[Jeje Lalpekhlua]], [[Harmanjot Khabra]] and [[Abhishek Das (footballer)|Abhishek Das]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Retain Players of Chennaiyin FC in ISL 2|url=http://www.footballlens.com/retain-players-of-chennaiyin-fc-for-isl-2-1682/|website=Footballlens|accessdate=17 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150517181929/http://www.footballlens.com/retain-players-of-chennaiyin-fc-for-isl-2-1682/|archive-date=17 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> They also signed [[Godwin Franco]] and [[Mehrajuddin Wadoo]]. On the last day of the transfer window, Chennaiyin FC announced that they had managed to sign back [[Stiven Mendoza]]. The season started with the team losing the first two games. Though the team managed to score points by winning at Goa and Mumbai, they lost another three games on the trot. By the third week of November, Chennaiyin were placed last in the league table. But, the team won four consecutive games to qualify for the playoffs, finishing at 3rd place in the regular season. They won the second season of the ISL by beating [[FC Goa]] 3\u20132 in the finals.\n\nFor the [[2016 Chennaiyin FC season|Third Season]], of [[Indian Super League]], they managed to retain six players namely, [[Mehrajuddin Wadoo]], [[Jayesh Rane]], [[Dhanachandra Singh]], [[Jeje Lalpekhlua]], [[Harmanjot Khabra]], [[Thoi Singh]] and [[Abhishek Das (footballer)|Abhishek Das]].<ref name=\"Chennaiyin Retained\">{{cite news|title=Quartet return from loan for ISL 2016|url=http://chennaiyinfc.com/quartet-returns-from-loan-for-isl-2016/|accessdate=1 June 2016|work=Chennaiyin Football Club|date=1 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630165508/http://chennaiyinfc.com/quartet-returns-from-loan-for-isl-2016/|archive-date=30 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Chennai signed [[John Arne Riise]] as the marquee player for the season. The season kicked off with a draw against Kolkata. Winning just three games through the season, the team finished in seventh place, just one point more than the last placed [[FC Goa]]. After a dismal season, it was announced on 6 March that [[Marco Materazzi]] and Chennaiyin parted ways on mutual consent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sports|first1=Reporter|title=Materazzi leaves Chennaiyin|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/chennaiyin-and-materazzi-part-ways/article17418920.ece|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=The Hindu|date=6 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sports|first1=Reporter|title=Materazzi and Chennaiyin part ways|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-chennaiyin-fc-part-ways-with-head-coach-marco-materazzi/story-jRaH8QCAeseedC6v90HojJ.html|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=Hindustan Times|date=6 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307081325/http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-chennaiyin-fc-part-ways-with-head-coach-marco-materazzi/story-jRaH8QCAeseedC6v90HojJ.html|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===John Gregory  (2017\u20132019)===\n[[File:John_gregory_CFC_coach.jpg|thumb|[[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]] led the team to ISL title in his first season]]\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n| GK_nat  = IND | GK  = [[Karanjit Singh|Karanjit]]\n| RB_nat = ESP | RB = [[I\u00f1igo Calder\u00f3n|Calder\u00f3n]]\n| RCB_nat = BRA | RCB  =  [[Ma\u00edlson Alves|Ma\u00edlson]]\n| LCB_nat = POR | LCB =[[Henrique Sereno|Sereno]]\n| LB_nat = IND | LB = [[Jerry Lalrinzuala|Lalrinzuala]]\n| RCM_nat = IND | RCM  =  [[Dhanpal Ganesh|Ganesh]]\n| LCM_nat  = IND| LCM  = [[Bikramjit Singh|Bikramjit]]\n| AM_nat  = BRA| AM =  [[Raphael Augusto|Augusto]]\n| RW_nat  =IND | RW  = [[Jeje Lalpekhlua|Jeje]]\n| LW_nat  =NED | LW  = [[Gregory Nelson|Nelson]]\n| CF_nat  = IND| CF  = [[Jeje Lalpekhlua|Lalpekhlua]]\n|caption=Lineup against [[Bengaluru FC]] in [[2017-18 Indian Super League Final]]\n|\n}}\nOn 3 July 2017, the club announced the appointment of former [[Aston Villa]] Manager [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]] as the head coach for the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://chennaiyinfc.com/chennaiyin-fc-appoint-englishman-john-gregory-as-head-coach/ |title=Chennaiyin FC appoint Englishman John Gregory as Head Coach |access-date=3 July 2017 |work=Chennaiyin FC |publication-date=3 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708022219/http://chennaiyinfc.com/chennaiyin-fc-appoint-englishman-john-gregory-as-head-coach/ |archive-date=8 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He took charge in September and the club traveled to Thailand for pre-season. Chennaiyin lost Gregory's first league game as head coach on 19 November against [[FC Goa]]. The team won its next three matches against [[Northeast United FC]], [[FC Pune City]] and [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]. [[Mumbai City FC]] brought Chennaiyin FC's winning run to an end with a battling 1\u20130 win at home inside the Mumbai Football Arena.<ref>{{cite web|title=ISL 2017, Match 22: Mumbai City FC vs Chennaiyin FC, 5 Talking Points|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/isl-2017-match-22-mumbai-city-fc-vs-chennaiyin-fc-5-talking-points|date=10 December 2017|access-date=21 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051851/https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/isl-2017-match-22-mumbai-city-fc-vs-chennaiyin-fc-5-talking-points|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The blues then travelled to Sree Kanteerava Stadium where they beat [[Bengaluru FC]] 2\u20131 in a tightly contested match.<ref>{{cite web|title=ISL, Bengaluru FC vs Chennaiyin FC, full score: BEN\u20091\u20132 CHE|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/live-isl-bengaluru-fc-vs-chennaiyin-fc-live-score/story-14wGf8aSwfHwZVEXGszjRM.html|website=hindustantimes.com|language=en|date=17 December 2017|access-date=21 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221184125/http://www.hindustantimes.com/football/live-isl-bengaluru-fc-vs-chennaiyin-fc-live-score/story-14wGf8aSwfHwZVEXGszjRM.html|archive-date=21 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Chennaiyin FC were held to a 1\u20131 draw when they faced Kerala Blasters at home in their next game. In spite of the draw, The Blues went top of the table with 13 points after seven games.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chennaiyin FC, Kerala Blasters draw 1\u20131 after thriller in Chennai: As it happened|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/indian-super-league-2017-18/kerala-blasters-vs-chennaiyin-fc-live-football-score-isl-indian-super-league-updates-4994702/|work=The Indian Express|date=22 December 2017|access-date=22 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223043704/http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/indian-super-league-2017-18/kerala-blasters-vs-chennaiyin-fc-live-football-score-isl-indian-super-league-updates-4994702/|archive-date=23 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The team went on to win the finals against Bangalore on their home ground and became the champions for the second time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chennaiyin FC conquer fortress Bengaluru to lift ISL 4 title|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/chennaiyin-fc-conquer-fortress-bengaluru-to-lift-isl-4-title/articleshow/63350853.cms|work=The Indian Express|date=18 March 2018|access-date=20 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320204822/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/chennaiyin-fc-conquer-fortress-bengaluru-to-lift-isl-4-title/articleshow/63350853.cms|archive-date=20 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Chennaiyin FC finished as runner-ups in AIFF Super Cup 2019 where they lost to [[FC Goa]] 2\u20131. Following Indian Super League glory in 2017\u201318, Chennaiyin became the first Indian club, representing the ISL, to play in the [[2019 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]], as they drew 0\u20130 with [[Colombo FC]] in [[Sri Lanka]] on 6 March 2019. A week later, they won the second leg 1\u20130 in Chennai to progress to the [[2019 AFC Cup group stage]]. Chennayin FC is the first ISL club to reach in Group stage of AFC Cup 2019 i.e. in Group E. They played a tie of 0\u20130 to [[Minerva Punjab FC]] on 3 April 2019 and won 2\u20130 to Nepalese club [[Manang Marshyangdi Club]] on 17 April 2019 whereby [[Ma\u00edlson Alves]] and [[Chris Herd]] also accompanied by win against [[Abahani Limited Dhaka]] by 1\u20130 and goal scorer was [[Anirudh Thapa]] 30 April 2019. On 19 June 2019 Chennaiyin FC faced a draw of 1\u20131 against [[Minerva Punjab F.C.]] where [[Mohammed Rafi]] secured a goal in the last minute of game. On [[John Gregory (footballer)|John Gregory]]'s 65th birthday the club announced that the coach's [[contract]] was renewed which and it will expire soon after the [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season]] . After losing the [[AFC Cup]] the club then made some shocking decisions by releasing their captain, [[Mailson Alves]] and the club's legend, [[Raphael Augusto]] as a preparation for the [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season]]. They also released some of the Indian players in their team which includes [[C.K. Vineeth]], [[Mohammed Rafi]], [[Halicharan Narzary]], [[Isaac Vanmalsawma]]. They then signed [[Nerijus Valskis]], [[Lucian Goian]], [[Drago\u0219 Fir\u021bulescu]] , [[Andr\u00e9 Schembri]] , [[Masih Saighani]] and [[Rafael Crivellaro]] to strengthen their squad. Following a horrible start to the [[2019-20 Indian Super League season]], John Gregory was fired by the team management on November 30 2019. This marked the end of the John Gregory era. Under his leadership [[Chennaiyin |Chennai]] won their second [[Indian Super League]] trophy.\n\n===Owen Coyle (2019-present)===\n\n{{football squad on pitch|align=right\n| GK_nat  = IND | GK  = [[Vishal Kaith|Kaith]]\n| RB_nat = IND | RB = [[Laldinliana Renthlei |Renthlei ]]\n| RCB_nat = BRA | RCB  =  [[Eli Sabi\u00e1|Sabi\u00e1]]\n| LCB_nat = ROM | LCB =[[Lucian Goian|Goian]]\n| LB_nat = IND | LB = [[Jerry Lalrinzuala|Lalrinzuala]]\n| RCM_nat = IND | RCM  =  [[Germanpreet Singh|Germanpreet]]\n| LCM_nat  = IND| LCM  = [[Anirudh Thapa|Thapa]]\n| AM_nat  = BRA| AM =  [[Rafael Crivellaro|Crivellaro]]\n| RW_nat  =MLT| RW  = [[Andr\u00e9 Schembri|Schembri]]\n| LW_nat  =IND | LW  = [[Lallianzuala Chhangte|Chhangte]]\n| CF_nat  = LTU| CF  = [[Nerijus Valskis|Valskis]]\n|caption=Lineup against [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] in [[2019-20 Indian Super League Final]]\n|\n}}\nOwen took the command of the club on December 4, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/isl/isl-interviews/chennaiyin-fc-coach-owen-coyle-interview-indian-super-league-isl-2019-2020-john-gregory-indian-football/article30170277.ece|title=Owen Coyle: I had other offers but felt a real connection with Chennaiyin FC|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> Under his guidance Chennaiyin faced 1-1 draw against [[Jamshedpur FC|Jamshedpur]], won 3-1 against [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]] and lost a dramatic game 4-3 to [[FC Goa|Goa]] in the initial days of Coyle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/football/isl-2019-20-highlights-jamshedpur-fc-vs-chennaiyin-fc-2417995.html|title=ISL 2019-20 HIGHLIGHTS, Jamshedpur FC vs Chennaiyin FC: Isaac Cancels Out Valskis Opener|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/football/isl-2019-20-highlights-chennaiyin-fc-vs-kerala-blasters-fc-2431225.html|title=ISL 2019-20 HIGHLIGHTS, Chennaiyin FC vs Kerala Blasters FC: Chennaiyin Beat Blasters in Dramatic Game at Home|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/isl/isl-2019-live-scores-fc-goa-vs-chennaiyin-fc-lineups-brandon-corominas-chhangte-thapa-valskis-schembri-indian-football/article30402565.ece|title=ISL 2019-20: Coro strike earns Goa 4-3 win over Chennayin FC|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>They lost to [[Odisha FC|Odisha]] on January 6, 2020 and won a game against [[Hyderabad FC|Hyderabad]] by 3-1.<ref>https://www.google.co.in/search?client=opera&hs=Dsf&sxsrf=ACYBGNTLJDkD66pKIEFLERtiMPgZ2ttcvQ%3A1579786293404&ei=NaApXtSSGJHVz7sP9aazwAM&q=chennaiyin+fc+vs+odisha&oq=chennaiyin+fc+vs+odisha&gs_l=psy-ab.3..0l8.333122.337553..338516...0.2..0.291.2415.0j2j9......0....1..gws-wiz.......0i71j35i39j0i273j0i67j0i131j0i20i263.ZUkkV_eejqs&ved=0ahUKEwiUgdvG6pnnAhWR6nMBHXXTDDgQ4dUDCAo&uact=5#sie=m;/g/11hdqk3l_h;2;/m/0ynr_sq;dt;fp;1;;</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/isl/isl-2019-20-chennaiyin-fc-3-1-hyderabad-fc-talking-points-valskis-crivellaro-asish-rai/article30537561.ece|title=ISL: Chennaiyin FC 3-1 Hyderabad FC - Talking points|access-date=2020-01-23|website=www.sportstar.thehindu.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Coyle era catapulted [[Chennaiyin FC]] to 4th from Bottom of the table(9th), thus earing them qualification for the playoffs.<ref>https://www.espn.in/football/match?gameId=569558</ref> He went on to guide Chennaiyin FC to the [[2020 Indian Super League Final|2020 ISL final]] after beating [[FC Goa]] 6-5 on aggregate over the two legs of the [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League playoffs|semifinals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/matchcentre/30701-chennaiyin-fc-vs-fc-goa|title=SEMI-FINAL 1 - 1ST LEG - COMPLETED|access-date=2020-03-06|website=www.indiansuperleague.com|language=en}}</ref>   <ref>https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/isl/isl-2020-live-score-fc-goa-vs-chennaiyin-fc-updates-playoff-semifinal-valskis-thapa-chhangte-rafael-corominas-boumous-coyle-brandon/article31001391.ece</ref>\n\nChennaiyin was threshed by [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] 3-1 even after [[Nerijus Valskis]] scored a goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/sports-news-atk-3-1-chennaiyin-fc-isl-2020-final-indian-super-league-has-become-more-professional-antonio-habas/348807|access-date=2020-03-16|title=ATK 3-1 Chennaiyin FC, ISL 2020 Final: Indian Super League Has Become More Professional \u2013 Antonio Habas|website=www.outlookindia.com|language=en}}</ref> [[Nerijus Valskis]] topped golden boot tally consequently, he was awarded ISL golden boot. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/isl/isl-2019-20-final-atk-roy-krishna-golden-boot-gurpreet-singh-sandhu-bengaluru-fc-hugo-boumous/article31070220.ece|access-date=2020-03-16|title=ISL final: Valskis wins Golden Boot, Gurpreet takes Golden Glove|website=www.sportstar.thehindu.com|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Stadium and attendance==\n{{Main|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium (Chennai)}}\n[[File:Jawaharlal_Nehru_Stadium_Chennai_panorama.jpg|thumb|Nehru Stadium, the home of Chennaiyin FC]]\nChennaiyin FC play their home matches at the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium (Chennai)|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]] in [[Chennai]] nicknamed the ''Marina Arena''. The stadium is located at Sydenhams Road, Park Town behind the [[Chennai Central railway station|Chennai Central suburban Railway station]] and [[Ripon Building]]. The stadium is named after [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[India]]'s first [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] and earlier hosted [[cricket]] [[Test cricket|Test Matches]] between 1956 and 1965.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nehru Stadium: Test Matches |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/58009.html?class=1;template=results;type=aggregate |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=17 June 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714131932/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/ground/58009.html?class=1;template=results;type=aggregate |archivedate=14 July 2012  }}</ref>\n\nChennaiyin FC has considerable support base with average attendance of over 10,000 over the first three seasons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Chennai-to-bleed-blue-again-this-football-season/articleshow/54524193.cms|title=Chennai to bleed blue again, this football season \u2013 Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=28 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218201257/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/City/Chennai/Chennai-to-bleed-blue-again-this-football-season/articleshow/54524193.cms|archive-date=18 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dtnext.in/Lifestyle/AroundTown/2016/10/01234934/Its-time-for-fans-to-show-their-loyalty.vpf|title=Supermachans show their loyalty through a flashmob|last=|first=|date=2 October 2016|work=|newspaper=dtNext.in|language=en-US|access-date=28 December 2016|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228195656/http://www.dtnext.in/Lifestyle/AroundTown/2016/10/01234934/Its-time-for-fans-to-show-their-loyalty.vpf|archive-date=28 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\nMost recently, the team declared the stadium's L1 stand of block H as an away stand.\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:center; margin-right:20px; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Season !! {{Tooltip|Attendance|Indian Super League average home attendances in Chennai}}\n|-\n|2014||22,095\n|-\n|2015||22,767\n|-\n|2016||22,139\n|-\n|2017\u201318||12,000\n|-\n|2018\u201319||15,000\n|-\n|}\n\n==Players==\n===Current squad<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaiyinfc.com/squad/|title=SQUAD}}</ref>===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=IND|pos=GK|name=[[Karanjit Singh]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=AFG|pos=DF|name=[[Masih Saighani]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=ROM|pos=DF|name=[[Lucian Goian]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|Captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=IND|pos=MF|name=[[Lallianzuala Chhangte]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=IND|pos=MF|name=[[Edwin Sydney Vanspaul]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=LTU|pos=FW|name=[[Nerijus Valskis]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=ROM|pos=MF|name=[[Drago\u0219 Fir\u021bulescu]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=IND|pos=MF|name=[[Thoi Singh]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=IND|pos=FW|name=[[Jeje Lalpekhlua]]|other=[[Vice Captain (association football)#Vice-captain|Vice-Captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=BRA|pos=DF|name=[[Eli Sabi\u00e1]]}}\n